(## 2. Learning from the Experience of Others) Tj
T*
T*
(One of the most powerful ways to grow in any workplace is to learn from the experience of) Tj
T*
(others.) Tj
T*
T*
(There is a lot we can learn from formal training, from courses, from manuals, from) Tj
T*
(onboarding materials. But there is also a lot of knowledge that lives in people. This is the) Tj
T*
(kind of knowledge that comes from doing the work, making mistakes, solving problems, and) Tj
T*
(learning what really works in practice.) Tj
T*
T*
(Sometimes, younger or newer team members think growth only means learning from books or) Tj
T*
(online resources. But one of the fastest ways to improve is to pay attention to the people) Tj
T*
(around you — especially those who have gone further in the journey.) Tj
T*
T*
(If somebody has been on the team longer than you, there is a reason to pay attention. They) Tj
T*
(may have already encountered the problems you are just beginning to face. They may know the) Tj
T*
(hidden challenges, the patterns, the likely mistakes, and the useful shortcuts.) Tj
T*
T*
(And this does not only apply to leaders. Even if someone is not officially a manager or) Tj
T*
(supervisor, they may still have valuable experience in a particular area. They may know how) Tj
T*
