(## 3. Mentorship as a Natural Part of Work) Tj
T*
T*
(This brings me to mentorship.) Tj
T*
T*
(When people hear mentorship, they sometimes imagine a very formal arrangement, with titles,) Tj
T*
(programs, meeting schedules, and structured sessions. Those things are good, but mentorship) Tj
T*
(is bigger than that. Mentorship can happen naturally in everyday work.) Tj
T*
T*
(A mentor is not only someone who gives advice. A mentor is someone whose experience helps) Tj
T*
(another person grow. Sometimes the mentor is a senior person. Sometimes it is a peer.) Tj
T*
(Sometimes it is even someone in a different department who has insight you can learn from.) Tj
T*
(The idea is simple: one person helps another person move forward by sharing what they know.) Tj
T*
T*
(And I think this is a very important culture to build.) Tj
T*
T*
(Because if every person only focuses on their own tasks and says, “that is not my) Tj
T*
(responsibility,” then knowledge gets stuck. But when people start seeing it as part of the) Tj
T*
(work to help others grow, then the organization becomes more than a workplace. It becomes a) Tj
T*
(place where people develop.) Tj
T*
T*
(A good mentor does not just give answers. A good mentor explains why something matters. They) Tj
T*
(help the other person build judgment. They show not only what to do, but how to think. That) Tj
T*
(is the kind of knowledge that stays useful for a long time.) Tj
T*
T*
(And on the other side, a good mentee is not passive. A good mentee asks questions, listens) Tj
T*
(carefully, pays attention, and applies what they learn. Mentorship works best when there is) Tj
T*
(humility on one side and generosity on the other.) Tj
T*
T*
(This matters because when mentorship becomes part of the culture, new people settle faster,) Tj
T*
(existing people grow stronger, and the organization does not need to start from zero every) Tj
T*
(time someone joins.) Tj
T*
T*
