T*
T*
(## 6. How to Receive Feedback Well) Tj
T*
T*
(Let me speak first to receiving feedback.) Tj
T*
T*
(A mature workplace is not one where nobody gets corrected. It is one where people know how) Tj
T*
(to hear correction properly.) Tj
T*
T*
(Receiving feedback well means being willing to listen before defending yourself. It means) Tj
T*
(not rushing to explain away everything. It means asking questions when something is not) Tj
T*
(clear. It means trying to understand the point being made instead of only reacting to the) Tj
T*
(discomfort.) Tj
T*
T*
(This is not always easy, because feedback can sometimes hit our pride. It can make us feel) Tj
T*
(exposed. It can remind us of what we got wrong. But if we want to grow, we must get) Tj
T*
(comfortable with not always being right.) Tj
T*
T*
(One important thing to remember is that feedback is not always about your intention.) Tj
T*
(Sometimes it is about impact. You may not have meant harm, confusion, or delay, but if that) Tj
T*
(is how your work affected others, then that is something worth hearing.) Tj
T*
T*
(So when feedback comes, a useful response is not, “That is not what I meant.”) Tj
T*
T*
(A better response is, “Thank you. Let me understand what happened and see how I can) Tj
T*
(improve.”) Tj
T*
T*
(That kind of attitude protects relationships, builds trust, and makes you easier to work) Tj
T*
(with. It also makes you stronger because you begin to grow faster from your experiences.) Tj
T*
T*
(## 7. How to Give Good Feedback) Tj
T*
T*
(The other side of the conversation is giving feedback.) Tj
T*
T*
(Good feedback is not harsh, vague, or embarrassing. It is thoughtful, specific, and helpful.) Tj
T*
(The goal is not to win an argument or prove that you are smarter. The goal is to help the) Tj
T*
(other person improve.) Tj
T*
